  "prompt": "According to the first law of motion, external force stops a body in uniform motion. What force do I have if I stop a rolling pin.?",
  "response": "I apologize, but there's a misunderstanding in your statement about the first law of motion. \n\nAccording to Newton's First Law of Motion (Law of Inertia):\n- A body at rest stays at rest\n- A body in uniform motion stays in uniform motion \n- UNLESS acted upon by an external force\n\nWhen you stop a rolling pin, you are applying an external force (friction) that causes the rolling pin to slow down and eventually stop. \n\nThe force you use to stop the rolling pin could be:\n1. Friction from your hand or a surface\n2. Mechanical resistance\n3. Your muscular force applied directly to the pin\n\nSo, in this case, you are providing the external force that changes the motion of the rolling pin, contrary to the initial statement in your question.\n\nThe specific force depends on:\n- How hard you press\n- The surface characteristics\n- The mass and initial velocity of the rolling pin",
